224
00:15:01,805 --> 00:15:05,001
Wait, I... I can see it.
It's... it's neon.

225
00:15:05,107 --> 00:15:08,100
- There's a neon sign.
- What does it say?

226
00:15:08,205 --> 00:15:11,502
Uh... there's... it's an "x"!

227
00:15:11,605 --> 00:15:15,202
Or letter... a "p", "r"...

228
00:15:23,407 --> 00:15:28,000
I don't know if this is the right place,
but it's the closest I can figure out.

229
00:15:28,105 --> 00:15:32,500
I think, someone got here
before we did.

230
00:15:32,705 --> 00:15:35,500
Mel, I'm sure the cops are coming.
You think this is a good idea?

231
00:15:35,608 --> 00:15:38,102
Well, it's the only way we can
free Bryan from whoever

232
00:15:38,207 --> 00:15:44,003
or whatever's controlling him.
I can't do that if he's in jail.

233
00:15:49,605 --> 00:15:51,503
It's the body from the morgue.

234
00:15:51,607 --> 00:15:54,003
That's him.

235
00:15:54,107 --> 00:15:56,001
Why is he making that noise?

236
00:15:56,105 --> 00:16:01,400
I think he's trying to set his own ribs.
Remember, he got hit by that car?

237
00:16:01,505 --> 00:16:04,101
Uhh... Bryan?

238
00:16:04,206 --> 00:16:06,102
It's me. Melinda.

239
00:16:06,207 --> 00:16:10,103
Do you remember?
You came to me.

240
00:16:12,408 --> 00:16:15,403
Do all your ghosts look like this?

241
00:16:15,505 --> 00:16:17,901
No.
He's a zombie.

242
00:16:18,005 --> 00:16:24,502
- Are you ready to cross over yet?
- I can't. Not till he's out of my body.

243
00:16:25,607 --> 00:16:29,103
No... I need to find her.

244
00:16:30,905 --> 00:16:33,300
Um... who are you?

245
00:16:33,408 --> 00:16:34,303
What's going on?

246
00:16:34,405 --> 00:16:37,600
There's another ghost inside
Bryan's body. He's just a kid.

247
00:16:37,707 --> 00:16:40,803
I have to find her.

248
00:16:41,405 --> 00:16:45,001
I need to finish the list.

249
00:17:06,807 --> 00:17:08,701
That's not normal.

250
00:17:08,805 --> 00:17:10,101
Yeah.

251
00:17:10,306 --> 00:17:12,601
Now I have to cross over 2 ghosts.

252
00:17:12,705 --> 00:17:16,503
The idea of a ghost in a dead body
is not as out there as it sounds.

253
00:17:16,608 --> 00:17:18,701
See, the thing that bothers me
is that usually when a ghost

254
00:17:18,807 --> 00:17:20,500
takes over a living body,
it's in short spurts.

255
00:17:20,605 --> 00:17:23,502
But this ghost is just running
full-bore over this person.

256
00:17:23,605 --> 00:17:26,300
Which takes everything you and I know
about the supernatural and pretty much

257
00:17:26,406 --> 00:17:28,701
just blows it out of the water.

258
00:17:28,807 --> 00:17:32,303
Hey, let's say Kurt Cobain
takes over Elvis' body.

259
00:17:32,408 --> 00:17:34,803
Does Elvis know new licks
on the guitar now?

260
00:17:34,906 --> 00:17:37,203
Is he grundge?
I mean... what happens?

261
00:17:37,307 --> 00:17:39,501
How much of your old body
do you bring into your new body?

262
00:17:39,605 --> 00:17:41,402
And... and do the hips still work?

263
00:17:41,507 --> 00:17:44,500
When I saw Bryan and the ghost
inside him, he looked like teenager.

264
00:17:44,606 --> 00:17:47,002
Except there was something wrong
with one of his eyes. It drooped.

265
00:17:47,106 --> 00:17:50,201
Drooped how? Like a muscular
spasm or a purposeful effect?

266
00:17:50,306 --> 00:17:51,702
Spasm.

267
00:17:51,805 --> 00:17:53,803
Spasm...

268
00:17:53,905 --> 00:17:57,701
Do you remember how clumsy that
ghost was that we saw on the video?

269
00:17:57,806 --> 00:18:00,801
- How he was having such a hard
time with his body? - Right.

270
00:18:00,908 --> 00:18:02,903
Yeah. And then I gave you
some weirdo line. I said,

271
00:18:03,007 --> 00:18:06,200
"the body and soul are literally
at war with each other."

272
00:18:06,305 --> 00:18:07,301
Blah, blah, blah.

273
00:18:07,407 --> 00:18:09,600
And you believed me,
'cause you always do.

274
00:18:09,708 --> 00:18:14,403
But I think your truth might be
a little more grounded.

275
00:18:14,506 --> 00:18:16,700
Is this what you saw, Melinda?

276
00:18:16,805 --> 00:18:17,902
Yeah, that's it.

277
00:18:18,007 --> 00:18:21,002
Yeah, well, this is very common
in degenerative diseases

278
00:18:21,107 --> 00:18:25,000
that affect motor skills.
Multiple sclerosis, cerebral palsy.

279
00:18:25,107 --> 00:18:28,100
Maybe the ghost that took over
this body had a similar handicap.

280
00:18:28,206 --> 00:18:30,903
- Uh, defect, whatever.
- He's not clumsy anymore.

281
00:18:31,008 --> 00:18:33,502
Right! He's not clumsy,
'cause he's in his new body.

282
00:18:33,607 --> 00:18:34,600
He's getting the lay of the land.

283
00:18:34,707 --> 00:18:38,202
He's saying, hey, this isn't the old
dead me. This is the new dead me.

284
00:18:38,305 --> 00:18:40,603
Not to mention,
living out his wildest dreams.

285
00:18:40,707 --> 00:18:41,301
What do you mean?

286
00:18:41,408 --> 00:18:44,003
If you couldn't walk, and you saw kids
running and jumping and doing

287
00:18:44,107 --> 00:18:47,403
all the things you dreamed of doing,
when you could, wouldn't you

288
00:18:47,508 --> 00:18:50,601
trade up for a new body? Wouldn't you
even come back from dead for a new body?

289
00:18:50,708 --> 00:18:53,302
Ok, so you're telling me that
this kid waited for somebody to die

290
00:18:53,408 --> 00:18:56,000
so he could come back and live
again without a handicap?

291
00:18:56,108 --> 00:18:58,703
Do you think it's easy being
this brilliant, Melinda?

292
00:18:58,808 --> 00:18:59,803
It's not.

293
00:18:59,905 --> 00:19:02,401
Sometimes it makes...

294
00:19:02,507 --> 00:19:04,203
it makes my head hurt, right here.

295
00:19:04,308 --> 00:19:06,003
Ok, well, there may be more to it than that.

296
00:19:06,105 --> 00:19:09,601
He said they had to find her
and finish some kind of list.

297
00:19:09,705 --> 00:19:10,702
What do you mean, "her"?

298
00:19:10,808 --> 00:19:12,502
He didn't say.

299
00:19:12,608 --> 00:19:14,303
- You might have a problem.
- Why?

300
00:19:14,408 --> 00:19:16,501
You said that ghost was 16 years old?

301
00:19:16,605 --> 00:19:18,701
No you're dealing with something
that's more unpredictable

302
00:19:18,805 --> 00:19:22,201
than a haitian death culture.
You're dealing with a teenage ghost

303
00:19:22,306 --> 00:19:26,500
inside a man's body with raging
hormones looking for a girl.

304
00:19:26,607 --> 00:19:29,200
Good luck.

305
00:20:08,305 --> 00:20:09,500
Hello?

306
00:20:09,607 --> 00:20:12,702
Hi, can I speak with Alyssa Adams, please?

307
00:20:12,805 --> 00:20:16,503
- This is Alyssa.
- Oh, great! Hi! This is Melinda Gordon.

308
00:20:16,605 --> 00:20:20,003
I'm actually looking for some
information on Jason Bennett.

309
00:20:20,106 --> 00:20:23,701
I read your, uh, memorial page
in the yearbook.

310
00:20:23,808 --> 00:20:25,802
Is this for the reunion reel?

311
00:20:25,906 --> 00:20:27,201
Sorry?

312
00:20:27,306 --> 00:20:29,101
For the 10-year reunion.

313
00:20:29,208 --> 00:20:34,001
I was already contacted about this,
and I think his parents are
contributing something.

314
00:20:34,107 --> 00:20:37,903
Yes! Yes, this is for the reunion.

315
00:20:38,008 --> 00:20:40,400
The one this weekend, yeah.

316
00:20:40,508 --> 00:20:42,601
You know, could we meet?

317
00:20:42,707 --> 00:20:47,902
Because I'd really like to
talk to you more about him.

318
00:20:56,205 --> 00:20:57,301
Hello?

319
00:20:57,406 --> 00:21:01,301
Sorry. Did I set the ringer too loud?

320
00:21:01,406 --> 00:21:04,102
Are you watching me?

321
00:21:04,207 --> 00:21:08,203
Only in the fun way.
Not in that crazy stalker way.

322
00:21:08,307 --> 00:21:11,300
What do you want?

323
00:21:11,607 --> 00:21:12,903
Say I'm sorry.

324
00:21:13,007 --> 00:21:16,102
You already did that.

325
00:21:16,207 --> 00:21:18,302
This is phase two.

326
00:21:18,407 --> 00:21:20,702
Look, you don't get to cue
your way out of this.

327
00:21:20,805 --> 00:21:23,500
You left me standing on the street
waiting for you.

328
00:21:23,608 --> 00:21:25,503
Do you have any idea
how humiliating that was?

329
00:21:25,608 --> 00:21:27,901
And then I had to walk
home after that?

330
00:21:28,005 --> 00:21:32,603
- I got no phone call, no explanation...
- But I have an explanation now.

331
00:21:32,707 --> 00:21:35,101
It's too late.

332
00:21:35,206 --> 00:21:40,702
And... since it took you this long,
you're even lamer than I thought.

333
00:21:40,807 --> 00:21:42,301
True.

334
00:21:42,407 --> 00:21:46,303
Completely, totally true. But...

335
00:21:46,605 --> 00:21:50,402
if I could just buy you a cup of
coffee, you know, or any dark liquid.

336
00:21:50,508 --> 00:21:52,400
Just have a minute.

337
00:21:52,507 --> 00:21:54,401
Tim, I gave you a minute.

338
00:21:54,507 --> 00:21:58,702
In fact, I gave you 30 long minutes.

339
00:21:59,005 --> 00:22:02,000
And you blew it.

340
00:22:05,605 --> 00:22:08,703
Well, we found one of his old yearbooks,

341
00:22:08,805 --> 00:22:11,101
and there was a reference
to a special girl.

342
00:22:11,205 --> 00:22:15,002
I was just wondering if you...

343
00:22:15,507 --> 00:22:20,003
We loved each other,
but... just friends.

344
00:22:25,607 --> 00:22:28,700
- He was so active.
- Yeah.

345
00:22:28,808 --> 00:22:33,101
He had muscular dystrophy, but he didn't
like to let one day go by

346
00:22:33,206 --> 00:22:35,300
without feeling like
he accomplished something.

347
00:22:35,405 --> 00:22:37,703
Like on the day we met,
it was in detention.

348
00:22:37,807 --> 00:22:38,900
Hmm, detention.

349
00:22:39,005 --> 00:22:43,001
He was in detention all the time.

350
00:22:43,207 --> 00:22:45,600
Do you know those old
showers in the chem lab

351
00:22:45,706 --> 00:22:49,601
with that emergency handle just in
case some kid sets himself on fire?

352
00:22:49,708 --> 00:22:55,701
He rolled himself under one of those
and shouted, "name the movie."

353
00:22:55,808 --> 00:23:00,901
Jason dripping wet in detention and
just furious that no one figured it out.

354
00:23:01,006 --> 00:23:04,300
- Flashdance?
- Yeah.

355
00:23:04,808 --> 00:23:07,902
I was the first to give him
the right answer.

356
00:23:08,008 --> 00:23:10,302
And he said, I had no choice.

357
00:23:10,405 --> 00:23:12,703
We would have to be
best friends from then on.

358
00:23:12,808 --> 00:23:15,700
It's been 10 years,
and I still miss him.

359
00:23:15,808 --> 00:23:19,503
We pulled so many schemes together.

360
00:23:19,607 --> 00:23:22,400
Just to feel like he could live.

361
00:23:22,506 --> 00:23:25,600
Is that why you took out
the page in the yearbook?

362
00:23:25,706 --> 00:23:28,002
"Not one day wasted"?

363
00:23:28,107 --> 00:23:30,400
Yeah.

364
00:23:31,008 --> 00:23:34,001
What's this list?

365
00:23:34,407 --> 00:23:39,402
At the end, Jason spent
a lot of time in the hospital.

366
00:23:39,505 --> 00:23:44,202
And it should have been
the worst time, but it wasn't.

367
00:23:44,305 --> 00:23:47,803
We dreamed up a list of things
to do before we died.

368
00:23:47,906 --> 00:23:52,303
- "Bungee jump off Grand Canyon"?
- Him.

369
00:23:52,506 --> 00:23:57,303
- "Open a studio in Paris."
- Yeah, so I could work on my collages.

370
00:23:57,407 --> 00:24:00,203
He knew that he would
never leave that room,

371
00:24:00,307 --> 00:24:05,203
and it couldn't stop him from
dreaming. It meant so much to him.

372
00:24:05,305 --> 00:24:08,100
Well, you kept the list. It must
have meant something to you too.

373
00:24:08,205 --> 00:24:09,800
No.

374
00:24:09,905 --> 00:24:10,801
The further the you get
from high school,

375
00:24:10,905 --> 00:24:15,002
the harder it is to make
your dreams come true.

376
00:24:15,107 --> 00:24:18,002
I still enjoy my art,
but I am not going to be selling it

377
00:24:18,108 --> 00:24:21,902
next to the Eiffel Tower anytime soon.

378
00:24:22,007 --> 00:24:25,900
Jason's the one that could
have done it. Not me.

379
00:24:26,005 --> 00:24:29,101
What about this last thing?
"Find Stephanie Hardwick"?

380
00:24:29,206 --> 00:24:31,003
Homecoming queen.

381
00:24:31,208 --> 00:24:33,300
The girl everybody loved.

382
00:24:33,405 --> 00:24:37,503
He wanted to find her
at the reunion and kiss her.

383
00:24:37,608 --> 00:24:38,603
Really?

384
00:24:38,707 --> 00:24:41,001
What guy wouldn't wanna
kiss the homecoming queen?

385
00:24:41,108 --> 00:24:45,703
But... why at the reunion?
I mean what was special about it?

386
00:24:45,805 --> 00:24:48,600
By 2007, Jason...

387
00:24:48,708 --> 00:24:51,600
he was sure they'd have
a cure for his M.D.

388
00:24:51,705 --> 00:24:54,402
And he'd be able to walk
into the reunion, and...

389
00:24:54,508 --> 00:24:58,301
Be the man he dreamed of being.

390
00:24:58,408 --> 00:25:00,102
I mean, who doesn't want to go
to their high school reunion

391
00:25:00,205 --> 00:25:01,900
- not looking like a rock star?
- Yeah, I know.

392
00:25:02,006 --> 00:25:06,000
Jason waited for a body he knew
would fit in at the reunion.

393
00:25:06,108 --> 00:25:09,700
Someone his own age, someone handsome.
Even the clothes he took.

394
00:25:09,808 --> 00:25:12,701
Yeah, just to impress miss Stephanie.

395
00:25:12,807 --> 00:25:15,102
Before he plants one on her.

396
00:25:15,206 --> 00:25:17,603
Oh, god. If he gets to her
before I can stop him...

397
00:25:17,708 --> 00:25:19,803
You should slip her
an altoid at least.

398
00:25:19,905 --> 00:25:24,100
Ok, you know what?
That is not funny.

399
00:25:25,706 --> 00:25:28,401
Here she is.

400
00:25:31,507 --> 00:25:35,602
You know, what if the body that
Jason took wasn't an accident?

401
00:25:35,707 --> 00:25:37,301
What do you mean?

402
00:25:37,407 --> 00:25:39,702
Stephanie Hardwick.
Homecoming queen.

403
00:25:39,807 --> 00:25:40,603
Yeah?

404
00:25:40,705 --> 00:25:44,401
Look at the homecoming king.

405
00:25:46,706 --> 00:25:48,700
Bryan and Jason were classmates.

406
00:25:48,806 --> 00:25:51,002
Jason didn't pick a random body.

407
00:25:51,107 --> 00:25:53,100
He picked the body.

408
00:25:53,207 --> 00:25:56,002
Of her date 10 years ago.

409
00:25:56,107 --> 00:25:59,303
"Varsity quarterback, valedictorian."

410
00:25:59,406 --> 00:26:02,403
Well, looks like the most popular guy
at school is gonna be going to his

411
00:26:02,505 --> 00:26:04,000
high school reunion after all.

412
00:26:04,105 --> 00:26:09,402
Yeah. He'll just be a lot
different than they remember.

413
00:26:37,805 --> 00:26:41,301
Usually a corpse is gonna
take 6 to 8 days to decay.

414
00:26:41,408 --> 00:26:42,902
We're only on day 3.

415
00:26:43,006 --> 00:26:45,903
That's assuming a perfect stress-free
environment here. Which we don't have.

416
00:26:46,006 --> 00:26:48,403
I mean, this guy is really putting
his body through the ringer.

417
00:26:48,507 --> 00:26:50,301
So how long will it be
before he breaks down?

418
00:26:50,406 --> 00:26:52,900
- I would say 6, maybe 8 hours.
- That soon?

419
00:26:53,006 --> 00:26:55,302
Maybe less, if he keeps jumping
through flaming hoops.

420
00:26:55,408 --> 00:26:57,201
My gosh, nature's running
its course on this guy.

421
00:26:57,306 --> 00:26:59,902
When we first found him,
he was trying to set his ribs.

422
00:27:00,007 --> 00:27:01,602
Well, he probably knows
his body won't hold out on him.

423
00:27:01,706 --> 00:27:05,203
So if you were trying to preserve
your body for as long as possible,
what would you do?

424
00:27:05,305 --> 00:27:08,900
I would get some kind of makeup.
Maybe the type a mortician would use.

425
00:27:09,005 --> 00:27:11,302
Cover up the appearance of dead skin.

426
00:27:11,407 --> 00:27:13,801
Ok. There's only one
mortuary in Grandview.

427
00:27:13,906 --> 00:27:15,601
Thanks.

428
00:27:15,706 --> 00:27:17,902
Jim?

429
00:27:32,405 --> 00:27:34,102
Hey, dead guy.

430
00:27:34,206 --> 00:27:36,303
Can I have my ring back?

431
00:27:36,407 --> 00:27:37,603
How's he been?

432
00:27:37,705 --> 00:27:41,403
Fine, once I restrained him.

433
00:27:41,706 --> 00:27:45,500
Is this really necessary?
I'm sorry, all right?

434
00:27:45,606 --> 00:27:47,203
Jason, we can't let you
go to that reunion.

435
00:27:47,308 --> 00:27:49,200
Why not?
I'm not gonna hurt anyone.

436
00:27:49,307 --> 00:27:51,702
No, but you wanted to kiss that
Stephanie Hardwick, you know?

437
00:27:51,807 --> 00:27:53,702
The last thing on your list? Come on.

438
00:27:53,806 --> 00:27:59,303
I was never actually gonna do that.
That was... that was just a goof.

439
00:27:59,405 --> 00:28:02,802
I just wanted to go and enjoy myself.

440
00:28:02,906 --> 00:28:06,601
Ok, even if that's true, your body's
breaking down, and you're not Bryan.

441
00:28:06,706 --> 00:28:09,100
You lived your life, and you
can't steal somebody else's.

442
00:28:09,208 --> 00:28:11,300
I didn't steal it.

443
00:28:11,406 --> 00:28:15,201
He abandoned it.
There's a big difference.

444
00:28:15,307 --> 00:28:19,201
You've been haunting him
this whole time, haven't you?

445
00:28:19,306 --> 00:28:21,603
Not haunting, just...

446
00:28:21,707 --> 00:28:23,802
checking in.

447
00:28:23,908 --> 00:28:26,403
I was curious to see what
mr. Most Likely To Succeed

448
00:28:26,506 --> 00:28:30,102
was gonna do with his life
after he dropped out of college.

449
00:28:30,207 --> 00:28:32,901
Whoa. Back up.
He dropped out of college?

450
00:28:33,006 --> 00:28:38,402
- He barely made it through a semester.
Isn't that right, Bryan? - Shut up.

451
00:28:38,506 --> 00:28:42,000
You wanna tell her what happened
after graduation, or should I?

452
00:28:42,105 --> 00:28:43,303
Shut up.

453
00:28:43,405 --> 00:28:49,103
- You don't know what it was like.
- Well, actually, I... do.

454
00:28:49,305 --> 00:28:53,500
You see, life wasn't so kind
after senior year.

455
00:28:53,608 --> 00:28:57,602
College ball was a little tougher,
classes took a little bit more effort,

456
00:28:57,707 --> 00:29:01,803
Bryan just couldn't juggle it all
like he could when he was 17,

457
00:29:01,907 --> 00:29:03,401
and he ended up getting
cut from the team,

458
00:29:03,507 --> 00:29:06,601
eventually dropped out from the school,
and basically spent the last 10 years

459
00:29:06,705 --> 00:29:10,503
studying his life from
the bottom of the class.

460
00:29:10,605 --> 00:29:12,300
Is that true?

461
00:29:12,408 --> 00:29:14,601
I mean he coasted on charm for a while.

462
00:29:14,706 --> 00:29:20,002
He was always good with the girls,
but even that faded.

463
00:29:20,106 --> 00:29:22,200
It gets to a point where girls
really aren't interested in guy

464
00:29:22,308 --> 00:29:26,800
who can't keep a job
for longer than 6 months.

465
00:29:26,907 --> 00:29:29,502
I mean, even Stephanie,
the homecoming queen

466
00:29:29,607 --> 00:29:33,100
moved on,
got engaged to that, uh...

467
00:29:33,208 --> 00:29:34,900
that guy, uh, Rick.

468
00:29:35,006 --> 00:29:38,703
Second string on the football team.

469
00:29:38,806 --> 00:29:40,901
That wasn't fair.

470
00:29:41,007 --> 00:29:43,703
He didn't deserve her.

471
00:29:43,807 --> 00:29:46,601
I mean, how could I show up
at a reunion and...

472
00:29:46,705 --> 00:29:51,400
- I didn't have a choice.
- He ended up in a bar, alone.

473
00:29:51,505 --> 00:29:55,100
Trying to convince a complete stranger
to go to our reunion with him.

474
00:29:55,206 --> 00:29:57,901
Come on! You'll be doing me
this huge favor.

475
00:29:58,005 --> 00:29:59,502
No, look. I just met you.

476
00:29:59,606 --> 00:30:01,600
Look, please.

477
00:30:01,706 --> 00:30:05,401
Oh, god. Just leave me alone.

478
00:30:05,508 --> 00:30:09,600
What do you do when you realize
you peaked in high school?

479
00:30:09,707 --> 00:30:13,002
I mean when you got nothing to
live for, how do you talk to all

480
00:30:13,107 --> 00:30:16,501
those people and all they remember
is how you used to be?

481
00:30:16,606 --> 00:30:20,702
Do you face them like you
freeze yourself in time

482
00:30:20,807 --> 00:30:26,201
and leave nothing but a memory
and a good-looking corpse?

483
00:30:27,707 --> 00:30:29,902
No!

484
00:30:33,607 --> 00:30:37,300
You were too scared to live?

485
00:30:37,607 --> 00:30:39,900
